<div id="review_3553677949" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3553677949" />
    <a title="JimZ" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz"><img alt="JimZ" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1575257175p2/99765491.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3553677949?book_show_action=true">Sep 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JimZ" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JimZ" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz">JimZ</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3553677949" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12211521857217047523">This sequel to Plainsong started out just fine for me–presenting its cast of characters in a coherent fashion. But then…I did not like some of the writing—I thought it was contrived. I like to get sucked into a story and not get jarred back into reality that here was an author who thought up a particular sentence and put it down in this book…when I’m supposed to be thinking of the characters who to me should exist in an alternative reality as I am reading along. Not: so why did Haruf write like </span>
  <span id="freeText12211521857217047523" style="display:none">This sequel to Plainsong started out just fine for me–presenting its cast of characters in a coherent fashion. But then…I did not like some of the writing—I thought it was contrived. I like to get sucked into a story and not get jarred back into reality that here was an author who thought up a particular sentence and put it down in this book…when I’m supposed to be thinking of the characters who to me should exist in an alternative reality as I am reading along. Not: so why did Haruf write like this? <br /><br />Can I give an example, then I’ll shut my pie-hole? Little Katie (I guess she is 3 or 4 years old) who is Victoria’s daughter is sitting at the kitchen table with Raymond, one of the endearing older brothers that we met in ‘Plainsong’, and who took Victoria into their house when she was pregnant.<br />•	“For dessert he got out a quart contained of chocolate ice cream and they ate some of that too while she continued to talk, sitting on her box at the table like some miniature black-haired black-eyed church woman at some basement bazaar, like some tiny Presbyterian female starved for the sound of her own voice.” <br />😮<br />What is this gobble-dee-gook? Just tell the story. Tell it like how you did in ‘Plainsong’. <br /><br />The entire book, to be fair, was not like this. There was some decent characterization…there was a man, Hoyt, that I would think all readers just plain out hated and despised and wish he was dead… There was some decent writing of course. It was a quick read. But there was enough of the sort of writing above that did not ring true for me and made me aware more times than I wanted that I was reading a novel by Kent Haruf (instead of being in Holt Colorado). As well some of what came out of the mouths of the characters seemed contrived. And…<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ it seemed a bit unrealistic to me how Rose Tyler jumps into the sack with Harold upon their second date. It just doesn’t seem to be part of Harold’s character to be willing and eager to do that.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> <br /><br />I feel bad in that I know so many GR friends liked this novel, and I am taking a contrary view. 🙁<br /><br />Note: I do like how he picks out titles…I really liked ‘Plainsong’ (any simple and unadorned melody or air) and also liked ‘Eventide’ (the time of evening; evening).<br /><br />Reviews:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/23/books/where-the-dust-motes-glow.html">https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/23/bo...</a><br />In The New Yorker’s Briefly Noted section May 24, 2004: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2004/05/31/eventide">https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/20...</a> <br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://readingmattersblog.com/2013/02/21/eventide-by-kent-haruf/">https://readingmattersblog.com/2013/0...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://2manybooks2littletime.com/2013/04/28/eventide-by-kent-haruf/">https://2manybooks2littletime.com/201...</a><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12211521857217047523" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

