    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1190012336" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1190012336" />
    <a title="Connie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4146473-connie"><img alt="Connie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514035275p2/4146473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1190012336?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Connie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Connie" href="/user/show/4146473-connie">Connie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4146473-connie?shelf=book-club-reads">book-club-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4146473-connie?shelf=2015">2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1190012336" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10912699025192202013">4.5 stars<br/><br/>Once again Kent Haruf has taken me back to the comfort of home with his writing. He is subtle, slowly capturing the reader to care about his characters. These are people I recognize, and feel comfortable with...no matter how long I have been away. The second in his trilogy, Eventide is a bit more coarse, not quiet as feel good as Plainsong. Each of these characters are facing difficult things in their lives...and for some of them it is coming at a very young age. There is sorrow in most</span>
  <span id="freeText10912699025192202013" style="display:none">4.5 stars<br /><br />Once again Kent Haruf has taken me back to the comfort of home with his writing. He is subtle, slowly capturing the reader to care about his characters. These are people I recognize, and feel comfortable with...no matter how long I have been away. The second in his trilogy, Eventide is a bit more coarse, not quiet as feel good as Plainsong. Each of these characters are facing difficult things in their lives...and for some of them it is coming at a very young age. There is sorrow in most of these stories. It makes me grieve for how times have changed from a life so simple, to a more complex road to navigate. Yet, these characters seem to find the light in there lives....even amidst the darkness. They come together as a community, something that is hard to find today.<br /><br /> Many people discuss that Haruf chooses not to use quotations in his dialogue. I tend to think of it as showing that perhaps these words are things said....or thoughts implied. These are people of few words....people who know the character of each other, without a word being said they know what the others thoughts are. This is very evident in the McPherson brothers....but at some level in the other characters as well.<br /><br /> He is a quiet writer, that tells a simple, yet beautiful story of characters that could be us....that captures the reader. I will miss him so.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10912699025192202013" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


